%T A230363 1307674368000,121645100408832000,25852016738884976640000,
%U A230363 15511210043330985984000000,10888869450418352160768000000,8222838654177922817725562880000000,10333147966386144929666651337523200000000
%N A230363 Factorials representable as b^2 + triangular(c).
%C A230363 Numbers k such that k! is representable as a sum of a square and a triangular number are listed in A394730.
%C A230363 k! is a term iff each prime factor congruent to 5 or 7 (mod 8) of 8*k!+1 comes in even degree. - _Max Alekseyev_, Mar 30 2026
%C A230363 1! = 1/2*1*(1+1), 3! = 1/2*3*(3+1) and 5! = 1/2*15*(15+1)/2 are triangular terms of the sequence. Next such term, if it exists is greater than 10000!. - _Farideh Firoozbakht_, Oct 18 2013
%H A230363 Max Alekseyev, <a href="/A230363/b230363.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..31</a>
%F A230363 A014133 INTERSECT A000142. - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 11 2014
%F A230363 a(n) = A394730(n)!. - _Max Alekseyev_, Mar 30 2026
%e A230363 13! = 66708^2+(1/2)*59616*(59616+1) = 78693^2+(1/2)*8298*(8298+1), so 13! = 6227020800 is in the sequence. What is the next term of the sequence which has more than one representation of the form b^2 + triangular(c)? - _Farideh Firoozbakht_, Oct 18 2013
%o A230363 (Python)
%o A230363 import math
%o A230363 f=1
%o A230363 for n in range(1, 1000000):
%o A230363     f *= n
%o A230363     t = b = 0
%o A230363     while t<=f:
%o A230363         x = f-t
%o A230363         a = math.isqrt(x)
%o A230363         if a*a==x:
%o A230363             print(f, end=", ")
%o A230363             break
%o A230363         b += 1
%o A230363         t = b*(b+1)//2
%Y A230363 Cf. A000142, A000290, A000217, A014133, A394730.
%K A230363 nonn,changed
%O A230363 1,3
